{"id":"1304.1429","submitter":"Tarek Sayed Ahmed","authors":"Tarek Sayed Ahmed","title":"Polyadic-like algebras without the amalgamation property","comments":"arXiv admin note: text overlap with arXiv:1303.7386","journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"math.LO","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  Usually when we have polyadic-like algebras, meaning that we have infinitary\nsubstitutions (that is substitutions moving infinitely many points) in the\nsimilarity type, then we get the superamalgamation property especially if this\nclass of algebras happen to be a variety. This for example happens for (full)\npolyadic algebras, full Heyting algebras and reducts of those using only\nfinitely many infinitary substitutions, like Sains Boolean and Heyting\nalgebras. (The last is studied by Sayed Ahmed) . In cylindric-like algebras\n(like quasi-polyadic algebras) when we do not have infinitary substitutions, we\ndo not get even the amalgamation property . In this paper, we give an example\nof a polyadic like variety (we have infinitary substitutions, in fact\ninfinitely many of them) for which the amalgamation property fails.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Thu, 4 Apr 2013 17:00:06 GMT"}],"update_date":"2013-04-05"}
{"id":"1304.1430","submitter":"Jing Li","authors":"Jing Li and David Jewitt","title":"Recurrent Perihelion Activity in (3200) Phaethon","comments":"23 pages, 7 figures, accepted by Astronomical Journal","journal-ref":null,"doi":"10.1088/0004-6256/145/6/154","report-no":null,"categories":"astro-ph.EP","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  We present a study of planet-crossing asteroid (3200) Phaethon at three\nsuccessive perihelia in 2009, 2010 and 2012, using the NASA STEREO spacecraft.\nPhaethon is clearly detected in 2009 and 2012, but not in 2010. In both former\nyears, Phaethon brightened unexpectedly by ~1 magnitude at large phase angles,\ninconsistent with the ~1 magnitude of steady fading expected from a discrete,\nmacroscopic body over the same phase angle range. With a perihelion distance of\n0.14 AU and surface temperatures up to ~1000 K, a thermal origin of this\nanomalous brightening is strongly suspected. However, simple thermal emission\nfrom Phaethon is too weak, by a factor >1000, to explain the brightening.\nNeither can ice survive on this body, ruling out comet-like sublimation. Our\npreferred explanation is that brightening occurs as a result of dust produced\nand ejected from Phaethon, perhaps by thermal fracture and/or thermal\ndecomposition of surface minerals when near perihelion. A contribution from\nprompt emission by oxygen released by desiccation of surface minerals cannot be\nexcluded. We infer an ejected mass of order 4x10^8 a_mm kg per outburst, where\na_mm is the mean dust radius in millimeters. For plausible dust radii, this\nmass is small compared to the estimated mass of Phaethon (~2x10^14 kg) and to\nthe mass of the Geminid stream (10^12 kg to 10^13 kg) with which Phaethon is\ndynamically associated. Perihelion mass-loss events like those observed in 2009\nand 2012 contribute to, but do not necessarily account for the Geminids stream\nmass.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Thu, 4 Apr 2013 17:04:20 GMT"}],"update_date":"2015-06-15"}
